<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-557-281  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 557 281.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 29 1990 v7 n43 p18(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Everex to unleash upgradable, 33MHz 486-based server. (EverexSystems Inc.'s Step Cube) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Skillings, Jonathan.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Everex Systems Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    EVRX.andO;Product:   Everex Systems StepCube (File server) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionMicrocomputersFile ServersMultiuser MicrocomputersComputer industryMultiprocessing.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Jonathan SkillingsandM;Everex Systems Inc. this week is expected to unwrap a 486-basedfloor-standing computer for multiuser PC environments.andM;The Step Cube will come standard with a 33MHz 486 processor, but in thefuture may be able to accommodate multiple processors.andP;  Due in December, itwill be capable of running DOS, Unix System V or Novell NetWare 386.andM;The basic configuration consists of a 3-1/2-inch floppy drive, eight ISAslots and a 400-watt power supply.andP;  It will feature 8M bytes of RAM,expandable to 64M bytes, and a 256K-byte second-level cache, said StevenDougherty, product manager at the Fremont, Calif., company.andM;System boards with eight or 12 Extended Industry Standard Architecture slotsare due by January, he said.andM;Four bays are dedicated to half-height, front-access, 5-1/4-inch drives, anda removable drive bay can hold two full-height or four half-height 5-1/4-inchdrives, or eight half-height 3-1/2-inch drives.andM;The Step Cube, 16.5 inches on each side, was designed to provide VARs withthe greatest flexibility in configuring systems to meet user needs forfile-server operations, Dougherty said, adding that it was built with an eyetoward expansion.andM;&quot;We overdesigned this system so we would be able to accommodate futureprocessors as they become available,&quot; he said.andM;Although exact pricing has not been determined, Dougherty said Everex expectsto price the Step Cube between $9,000 to $14,000.andP;  It will be availablethrough VARs.andM;Although multiuser applications are appearing relatively slowly, Everex andother PC makers are delivering machines now to stake out their claims to ashare of the market, analysts said.andM;Everex Systems Inc. can be reached at (800) 821-0806.andO;</TEXT></DOC>